Validation of sdarr and sdarr.lazy

Though no exhaustive validation has been conducted, the Reference Data Set E3076-DS1(2018) File 01 mentioned in ASTM E3076-18 as …available for download from ASTM at https://www.astm.org/ COMMITTEE/E08.htm, under the heading, Additional Information… has been used to check the results of this implementation. The Reference Data Set E3076-DS1(2018) File 01 was also analyzed as benchmark in NIST Technical Note 2050 by E. Lucon with minor differences to the expected results listed in the standard.

Validation Result

At first glimpse, the results of the analysis using the random sub-sampling variant of the SDAR-algorithm sdarr.lazy() are not identical to the results given in ASTM E3076-18 or the results from NIST Technical Note 2050 by E. Lucon (except for omitting any rounding).
However, when considering the 95% confidence intervals (additionally given with the result from sdarr() and sdarr.lazy()) obtained from the final fitting in the standard SDAR-algorithm, the results of the lazy variant are well within the 95%-CI of the standard variant. There is only a minor difference in the y-range of the final fits resulting in slightly different final results.
Comparing the regression curves of sdarr.lazy() and sdarr() over the mechanical data, you see that there is practically no difference (zoom in …a lot… to see a difference).

Conclusions

Even though this is more a benchmarking than a real validation, the results of sdarr() are practically identical to the results listed in ASTM E3076-18 and in NIST Technical Note 2050 by E. Lucon. Considering the 95% confidence intervals of the fitting results, same seems true for the random sub-sampling modification used in sdarr.lazy().
